class Solution {
public:
    int trailingZeroes(int n) {
        int count = 0;
        while(n > 0){
            n /= 5;         // Divide n by 5
            count += n;     // Add to count
        }
        return count;
    }
};
ğŸ§  Why This Works
Each division by 5 tells us how many numbers â‰¤ n are divisible by 5 (i.e., contribute at least one 5).

We continue dividing by 5 to account for:

Numbers like 25 (5Ã—5) contribute two 5s

Numbers like 125 (5Ã—5Ã—5) contribute three 5s, etc.

So we add n/5 + n/25 + n/125 + ... to get the total count of 5s.

ğŸ¤” Why Not Count the 2s?
You can, but itâ€™s unnecessary. There are more 2s than 5s in any factorial. So they donâ€™t limit the number of 10s.

Hence, we only count the number of 5s.

